Data Collection and Parsing¶

Twitch is a live streaming service that is mainly used for video game streaming, but also for other forms of entertainment and creative content. It was launched in 2011 and has since become one of the most popular streaming platforms, with millions of daily active users. People can watch live streams, interact with other users and streamers, donate to their favorite content creators to support their work, and discover new and exciting content. Through this tutorial, we can explore and analyze data about Twitch and its users.

First, we pulled data from this dataset on Kaggle on the top 1000 Twitch streamers (based on watch time) from a specific year. This dataset includes information on each of the listed streamers, such as number of followers, followers gained over the past year, and total watch time in minutes.

First, we must import several Python packages that will allow us to wrangle and visualize the data.

requests: send HTTP requests pandas: manipulate and analyze data using dataframes numpy: perform operations on large, multidimensional arrays and matrices matplotlib: visualize data through graphs and charts seaborn: (based on matplotlib) also create graphics of statistical information

We downloaded the .csv file containing the dataset and uploaded it to our Jupyter folder. Then, using the pandas software library, the data within the csv file is put into a dataframe using the function "read_csv". This will allow us to perform various functions that will help us analyze the data. Thankfully, the data is already well organized in a .csv file, so there is no need to do any extra collection or parsing.

In [1]:

Data Management/Representation¶

Cleaning Data¶

Data cleaning is incredibly important when handling datasets. It helps to ensure that the data being used is accurate and usable, as even small errors can greatly impact the results. Tasks to clean data include identifying and correcting errors, dealing with missing values, and standardizing formats. We can clean the data by dropping any rows (using pandas dropna function) that had NaN or None values, since they are inconsistent with the rest of the data. After executing the dropna function, we can see that there were no rows with NaN or None values, so the data set was already sufficiently cleaned.

In [2]:
df = df.dropna()

When we analyze the data, the streamers rankings within the top 1000 may be helpful to draw statistical information from. We can create a new column that holds the rank for each of the content creators by using the reset_index pandas function. This resets the index to 0 and we can copy each index value into the rows. Then, we can add 1 to every entry so that the #1 streamer starts at rank 1 instead of 0.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

What is exploratory data analysis¶

Exploratory data analysis is a way of analyzing and understanding data that focuses on identifying patterns, trends, and relationships in the data. It involves the use of statistical graphics and other visualizations. We can explore the data now, as we have finished cleaning and tidying.

First, lets explore how watch time (in minutes) is distributed amongst the streamers by rank, as this dataset is based on watch time. We can use matplotlib functions to create a bar plot that displays how much watch time each of the top 1000 streamers get.

In [5]:
# Set the figure size and label font sizes
# This will make the chart easier to read
plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
plt.rc('ytick', labelsize=20)
plt.rc('axes', labelsize=25)
sns.barplot(x = "ranking", y = "watch_time", data = df).set(title="Channel Count by Language")
plt.xticks([])
plt.show()

The graph above shows the streamers ranking on the x-axis and the watch time in minutes on the y-axis. As shown, higher ranked streamers have exponentially more watch time than lower ranked streamers. The bar plot shows that the relationship between watch time and streamer rank is an exponential decay function, as the watch time for each streamer decreases proportionally to the previous.

Streaming Times vs Followers Gained¶

Next, lets see if there is any correlation between how much and how often a streamer was live, and the number of followers they gained over the course of one year. This might be useful information for content creators (that want to grow their channel) to know because it may help them figure out how to get the most followers with the most optimal streaming time. To start this process, lets clean up the data so that we can only see the channel names, amount of time spent streaming in minutes, and the amount of followers gained over the year that this data was collected. We can use df.filter (from pandas library) to create a new dataframe that holds only those specific columns and filters the rest of them out.

In [15]:
# df.filter is used to create a new dataframe where only the columns we specify are present.

Hypothesis Testing¶

The null hypothesis is a statement that claims that there is no effect or association between two variables. It is important to use when testing the significance of differences in experiments or observations.

Streaming Times vs Followers Gained¶

Our null hypothesis is that there is no relationship between the amount of time that a streamer streams and the number of followers gained. We can explore this through seaborns regplot function, where it will plot data and a linear regression model fit.

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.rc('xtick', labelsize=20)
plt.rc('ytick', labelsize=20)
plt.rc('axes', labelsize=25)
# A seaborn regression plot is similar to a scatterplot but also includes a linear regression line.
sns.regplot(x = "stream_time", y = "followers_gained", data = streaming_followers_gained_df).set(title="Time Spent Streaming vs. Followers Gained Over the Course of a Year")
plt.show()

This visualization does not show much correlation between the stream time and number of followers gained, and there are numerous outliers. Lets calculate the p-value, as if it is more than 0.5, then we can safely accept the null hypothesis.

In [20]:
# Import from sklearn and statsmodels so we can model our data and find p-values
from sklearn import datasets, linear_model
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import statsmodels.api as sma
y = streaming_followers_gained_df['followers_gained']
x = streaming_followers_gained_df['stream_time']
x2 = sma.add_constant(x)
stream_follow_model = sma.OLS(y, x2).fit()
print(stream_follow_model.summary())

# Loop through each of the top five languages and create a linear regression plot and summary
for lang in top_languages:
    curr_df = df.loc[df['language'] == lang]
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.rc('xtick', labelsize=20)
    plt.rc('ytick', labelsize=20)
    plt.rc('axes', labelsize=25)
    title_str = "Time Spent Streaming vs. Followers Gained Over the Course of a Year " + lang
    sns.regplot(x = "stream_time", y = "followers_gained", data = curr_df).set(title= title_str)
    plt.show()
    y = curr_df['followers_gained']

Communication of Insights Attained¶

Streaming Times vs Followers Gained¶

Based on the plotted data and linear regression model, we can conclude that streaming for longer results in less followers gained (negative correlation). Channels like Riot Games and Asmongold, for example, are outliers in the scatter plot as they have gained a lot of followers with relatively low stream time. The opposite is true as well for channels like MarketTradersTV or jmjdoc, who had high stream times but low follower gain.

Watch Times vs Followers Gained¶

We can conclude that longer watch times result in more followers gained (positive correlation). The number for watch time and number for followers gained are decently proportional for most streamers, so it is clear that the longer people watch a stream, the more likely they are to follow the creator.

What does this all mean?¶

This data may be helpful to people who want to become popular live streamers, as the information drawn from this tutorial shows what you can do to gain more followers. We know that the correlation between stream time and followers gained is negative, so that shows that it is not optimal to try and gain popularity on Twitch by just streaming a lot. What matters is that people watch the content, as they are more likely to follow and support streamers that produce good content. Overall, this tutorial has shown how the data science pipeline works through sets of data, so that we can better understand data science and the significance of relationships and observations.
